    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Arca Manioni, <choice><reg>militi</reg><orig>milete</orig></choice>, <supplied reason="omitted">d</supplied>e nume
                    <lb n="2" break="no"/>ro Bruc<choice><corr>t</corr><sic>h</sic></choice>er<supplied reason="omitted">or</supplied>um et si quis eam
                    <lb n="3"/>aperuerit, ut <measure type="mutilatory_sanction"><choice><reg>manus</reg><orig>mani</orig></choice> <choice><reg>praecidantur</reg><orig>precidantur</orig></choice></measure>
                    <lb n="4"/>aut in <choice><reg>fisco</reg><orig>fesco</orig></choice> det <measure type="fine" unit="roman_pound" commodity="gold" quantity="2">auri pondo <choice><reg>duo</reg><orig>doa</orig></choice></measure>.
                    <lb n="5"/><expan><abbr>cons</abbr><ex>ulibus</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>n</abbr><ex>ostris</ex></expan> Arcadio
                    <lb n="6"/>et <supplied reason="omitted">H</supplied>onorio <expan><ex>Au</ex><abbr>g</abbr><ex>u</ex><abbr>st</abbr><ex>i</ex><abbr>s</abbr></expan>.
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>The <term xml:lang="la">arca</term> of <persName ref="#manio" xml:lang="la">Manio</persName>, a soldier of the <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term>; and should anyone open it, let his hands be cut off, or let him pay two pounds of gold to the <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term>.</p>
                <p>During the consulship of our lords <persName ref="#arcadius">Arcadius</persName> and <persName ref="#honorius">Honorius</persName> Augusti.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Arca di <persName ref="#manio">Manione</persName>, soldato del <term xml:lang="la">numerus</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term>; e se qualcuno la aprirà, gli vengano recise le mani oppure versi al <term xml:lang="la">fiscus</term> due libbre (romane) d'oro.</p>
                <p>Sotto i nostri consoli <persName ref="#arcadius">Arcadio</persName> e <persName ref="#honorius">Onorio</persName> Augusti.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#manio" xml:lang="la">Manio</persName> was a <term xml:lang="la">miles</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term>. The <term xml:lang="la">auxilium palatinum</term> of the <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term> is recorded as being stationed in Gaul (<term xml:lang="la">ND occ</term>. 5, 187; 7, 68).
                </p>
                <p>
                    The inscription does not specify the beneficiary of this sarcophagus.
                </p>
                <p>
                    This is the only Latin inscription on a sarcophagus within the necropolis to provide a date, corresponding to the joint consulship of <persName ref="#arcadius">Arcadius</persName> and <persName ref="#honorius">Honorius</persName>, the sons of <persName ref="#theodosius">Theodosius</persName>. They served as consuls together in 394, 396, and 402 AD.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The replacement of certain <g type="pl">i</g> letters with <g type="pl">e</g>, as in the case of <term xml:lang="la">milete</term> instead of <term xml:lang="la">militi</term>, likely reflects the pronunciation of the period, during which the Latin <g type="pl">short i</g> progressively opened until it became an <g type="pl">e</g>.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="it">
                <p>
                    <persName ref="#manio" xml:lang="la">Manio</persName> era un <term xml:lang="la">miles</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term>. L'<term xml:lang="la">auxilium palatinum</term> dei <term xml:lang="la">Bructeri</term> risulta dislocato in Gallia (<term xml:lang="la">ND occ</term>. 5, 187; 7, 68).
                </p>
                <p>
                    Nell'iscrizione non è specificato il dedicatario di questo sarcofago.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Si tratta dell'unica iscrizione latina di un sarcofago all'interno della necropoli che presenta una datazione, corrispondente al consolato congiunto di <persName ref="#arcadius">Arcadio</persName> e <persName ref="#honorius">Onorio</persName>, i figli di <persName ref="#theodosius">Teodosio</persName>. Costoro furono consoli nel 394, 396 e nel 402 d.C.
                </p>
                <p>
                    La sostituzione di alcune lettere <g type="pl">i</g> con le <g type="pl">e</g>, come nel caso di <term xml:lang="la">milete</term> al posto di <term xml:lang="la">militi</term>, sembra rappresentare la pronuncia dell'epoca, dove tendenzialmente la <g type="pl">i breve</g> latina si aprì progressivamente fino a diventare una <g type="pl">e</g>.
                </p>
            </div>
